msgid "At this point the part looks like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_selectors.rst:131
msgid "Step 6: Fillet the top perimeter Edge"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_selectors.rst:133
msgid "The final step is to apply a fillet to the top perimeter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_selectors.rst:142
msgid "Here we're using the :func:`~operations_generic.fillet` operation which needs two things: the edge(s) to fillet and the radius of the fillet. To provide the edge, we'll use more selectors as described in the following sub-steps."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_selectors.rst:148
msgid "Step 6a: Extract all the Edges"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_selectors.rst:150
msgid "Much like selecting Faces in Step 3a, we'll select all of the ``example`` part's edges with ``example.edges()``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_selectors.rst:154
msgid "Step 6b: Filter the Edges for circles"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_selectors.rst:156
msgid "Since we know that the edge we're looking for is a circle, we can filter the edges selected in Step 6a for just those that are of geometric type ``CIRCLE`` with ``example.edges().filter_by(GeomType.CIRCLE)``. This step removes all of the Edges of the hexagon hole."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_selectors.rst:162
msgid "Step 6c: Sort the circles by radius"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_selectors.rst:164
msgid "The perimeter are the largest circles - the central cylinder must be excluded - so we'll sort all of the circles by their radius with: ``example.edges().filter_by(GeomType.CIRCLE).sort_by(SortBy.RADIUS)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_selectors.rst:169
msgid "Step 6d: Slice the list to get the two largest"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_selectors.rst:171
msgid "We know that the ``example`` part has two perimeter circles so we'll select just the top two edges from the sorted circle list with: ``example.edges().filter_by(GeomType.CIRCLE).sort_by(SortBy.RADIUS)[-2:]``.  The syntax of this slicing operation is standard python list slicing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_selectors.rst:177
msgid "Step 6e: Select the top Edge"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_selectors.rst:179
msgid "The last sub-step is to select the top perimeter edge, the one with the greatest Z value which we'll do with the ``sort_by(Axis.Z)[-1]`` method just like Step 3b - note that these methods work on all Shape objects (Edges, Wires, Faces, Solids, and Compounds) - with: ``example.edges().filter_by(GeomType.CIRCLE).sort_by(SortBy.RADIUS)[-2:].sort_by(Axis.Z)[-1]``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_selectors.rst:187
msgid "Conclusion"
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_selectors.rst:189
msgid "By using selectors as we have in this example we've used methods of identifying features that are robust to features changing within the part. We've also avoided the classic CAD \"Topological naming problem\" by never referring to features with names or tags that could become obsolete as the part changes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../build123d/docs/tutorial_selectors.rst:195
msgid "When possible, avoid using static list indices to refer to features extracted from methods like ``edges()`` as the order within the list is not guaranteed to remain the same."
msgstr ""
